</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Congestive hepatopathy (CH) refers to hepatic abnormalities that result from passive hepatic venous congestion. Prolonged exposure to elevated hepatic venous pressure may lead to liver fibrosis and cirrhosis. Liver dysfunction and corresponding clinical signs and symptoms typically manifest late in the disease process. Recognition of CH at imaging is critical because advanced liver fibrosis may develop before the condition is suspected clinically. Characteristic findings of CH on conventional images include dilatation of the inferior vena cava and hepatic veins; retrograde hepatic venous opacification during the early bolus phase of intravenous contrast material injection; and a predominantly peripheral heterogeneous pattern of hepatic enhancement due to stagnant blood flow. Extensive fibrosis can be seen in chronic or severe cases. Hyperenhancing regenerative nodules that may retain hepatobiliary contrast agents are often present. Magnetic resonance (MR) elastography can show elevated liver stiffness and may be useful in evaluation of fibrosis in CH because it can be incorporated easily into routine cardiac MR imaging. Preliminary experience with MR elastography suggests its future use in initial evaluation of patients suspected of having CH, for monitoring of disease, and for assessment after therapy. To facilitate appropriate workup and treatment, radiologists should be familiar with findings suggestive of CH at radiography, ultrasonography, computed tomography, MR imaging, and MR elastography. In addition, knowledge of underlying pathophysiology, comparative histologic abnormalities, and extrahepatic manifestations is useful to avoid diagnostic pitfalls and suggest appropriate additional diagnostic testing.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150207">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150207">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig1a.jpeg" height="922" width="1512" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Histologic changes in the hepatic parenchyma in response to chronic venous congestion. <b>(a–d)</b> Drawings show the progression of histologic changes. <b>(a)</b> Congestion of the central vein (arrow) results in sinusoidal dilatation and perisinusoidal edema (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Persistent congestion results in perisinusoidal hemorrhaging (arrow), fatty changes (yellow dots), and loss of hepatocytes around the central vein. <b>(c)</b> Fibrosis (white areas) first occurs around the central vein and perisinusoidal parenchyma. <b>(d)</b> In later stages, fibrosis bridges the central veins (arrows) and will eventually result in parenchymal remodeling. (Fig 1a–1d reprinted, with permission, from Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph shows prominent sinusoidal dilatation (arrows) and centrilobular perisinusoidal fibrosis (blue stain) extending from a central vein (★). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig1b.jpeg" height="922" width="1638" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Histologic changes in the hepatic parenchyma in response to chronic venous congestion. <b>(a–d)</b> Drawings show the progression of histologic changes. <b>(a)</b> Congestion of the central vein (arrow) results in sinusoidal dilatation and perisinusoidal edema (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Persistent congestion results in perisinusoidal hemorrhaging (arrow), fatty changes (yellow dots), and loss of hepatocytes around the central vein. <b>(c)</b> Fibrosis (white areas) first occurs around the central vein and perisinusoidal parenchyma. <b>(d)</b> In later stages, fibrosis bridges the central veins (arrows) and will eventually result in parenchymal remodeling. (Fig 1a–1d reprinted, with permission, from Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph shows prominent sinusoidal dilatation (arrows) and centrilobular perisinusoidal fibrosis (blue stain) extending from a central vein (★). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig1c.jpeg" height="956" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Histologic changes in the hepatic parenchyma in response to chronic venous congestion. <b>(a–d)</b> Drawings show the progression of histologic changes. <b>(a)</b> Congestion of the central vein (arrow) results in sinusoidal dilatation and perisinusoidal edema (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Persistent congestion results in perisinusoidal hemorrhaging (arrow), fatty changes (yellow dots), and loss of hepatocytes around the central vein. <b>(c)</b> Fibrosis (white areas) first occurs around the central vein and perisinusoidal parenchyma. <b>(d)</b> In later stages, fibrosis bridges the central veins (arrows) and will eventually result in parenchymal remodeling. (Fig 1a–1d reprinted, with permission, from Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph shows prominent sinusoidal dilatation (arrows) and centrilobular perisinusoidal fibrosis (blue stain) extending from a central vein (★). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig1d.jpeg" height="956" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Histologic changes in the hepatic parenchyma in response to chronic venous congestion. <b>(a–d)</b> Drawings show the progression of histologic changes. <b>(a)</b> Congestion of the central vein (arrow) results in sinusoidal dilatation and perisinusoidal edema (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Persistent congestion results in perisinusoidal hemorrhaging (arrow), fatty changes (yellow dots), and loss of hepatocytes around the central vein. <b>(c)</b> Fibrosis (white areas) first occurs around the central vein and perisinusoidal parenchyma. <b>(d)</b> In later stages, fibrosis bridges the central veins (arrows) and will eventually result in parenchymal remodeling. (Fig 1a–1d reprinted, with permission, from Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph shows prominent sinusoidal dilatation (arrows) and centrilobular perisinusoidal fibrosis (blue stain) extending from a central vein (★). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig1e.jpeg" height="1438" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span>. Histologic changes in the hepatic parenchyma in response to chronic venous congestion. <b>(a–d)</b> Drawings show the progression of histologic changes. <b>(a)</b> Congestion of the central vein (arrow) results in sinusoidal dilatation and perisinusoidal edema (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Persistent congestion results in perisinusoidal hemorrhaging (arrow), fatty changes (yellow dots), and loss of hepatocytes around the central vein. <b>(c)</b> Fibrosis (white areas) first occurs around the central vein and perisinusoidal parenchyma. <b>(d)</b> In later stages, fibrosis bridges the central veins (arrows) and will eventually result in parenchymal remodeling. (Fig 1a–1d reprinted, with permission, from Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph shows prominent sinusoidal dilatation (arrows) and centrilobular perisinusoidal fibrosis (blue stain) extending from a central vein (★). (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig2.jpeg" height="1744" width="1799" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Schematic diagram shows the pathophysiologic mechanism of liver injury as a result of congestive hepatopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig3a.jpeg" height="1272" width="1463" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Multimodality imaging findings in a patient with advanced <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> due to constrictive pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> Lateral chest radiograph shows pericardial calcification (arrowhead) and pleural effusion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Spectral Doppler US image of the middle hepatic vein shows a large diastolic antegrade flow (arrow) and extra diastolic retrograde pulsation (arrowhead) corresponding to abrupt termination of cardiac filling due to the rigid pericardium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) images at the level of the heart <b>(c)</b> and liver <b>(d)</b> show pericardial calcification (arrowhead in <b>c</b>), pleural effusion, ascites (arrows), nodular cirrhotic liver, and splenomegaly. No evidence of portosystemic shunting is seen on the CT images, despite the findings of advanced hepatic cirrhosis, ascites, and splenomegaly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig3b.jpeg" height="1272" width="1487" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Multimodality imaging findings in a patient with advanced <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> due to constrictive pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> Lateral chest radiograph shows pericardial calcification (arrowhead) and pleural effusion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Spectral Doppler US image of the middle hepatic vein shows a large diastolic antegrade flow (arrow) and extra diastolic retrograde pulsation (arrowhead) corresponding to abrupt termination of cardiac filling due to the rigid pericardium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) images at the level of the heart <b>(c)</b> and liver <b>(d)</b> show pericardial calcification (arrowhead in <b>c</b>), pleural effusion, ascites (arrows), nodular cirrhotic liver, and splenomegaly. No evidence of portosystemic shunting is seen on the CT images, despite the findings of advanced hepatic cirrhosis, ascites, and splenomegaly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig3c.jpeg" height="1236" width="1463" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Multimodality imaging findings in a patient with advanced <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> due to constrictive pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> Lateral chest radiograph shows pericardial calcification (arrowhead) and pleural effusion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Spectral Doppler US image of the middle hepatic vein shows a large diastolic antegrade flow (arrow) and extra diastolic retrograde pulsation (arrowhead) corresponding to abrupt termination of cardiac filling due to the rigid pericardium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) images at the level of the heart <b>(c)</b> and liver <b>(d)</b> show pericardial calcification (arrowhead in <b>c</b>), pleural effusion, ascites (arrows), nodular cirrhotic liver, and splenomegaly. No evidence of portosystemic shunting is seen on the CT images, despite the findings of advanced hepatic cirrhosis, ascites, and splenomegaly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig3d.jpeg" height="1236" width="1485" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Multimodality imaging findings in a patient with advanced <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> due to constrictive pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> Lateral chest radiograph shows pericardial calcification (arrowhead) and pleural effusion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Spectral Doppler US image of the middle hepatic vein shows a large diastolic antegrade flow (arrow) and extra diastolic retrograde pulsation (arrowhead) corresponding to abrupt termination of cardiac filling due to the rigid pericardium. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) images at the level of the heart <b>(c)</b> and liver <b>(d)</b> show pericardial calcification (arrowhead in <b>c</b>), pleural effusion, ascites (arrows), nodular cirrhotic liver, and splenomegaly. No evidence of portosystemic shunting is seen on the CT images, despite the findings of advanced hepatic cirrhosis, ascites, and splenomegaly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig4a.jpeg" height="1390" width="1893" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Spectral Doppler US waveform images of portal venous flow in two patients. <i>AC</i> = angle of correction, <i>MPV</i> = main portal vein, <i>PV</i> = portal velocity. <b>(a)</b> Image shows that typical antegrade portal venous flow is hepatopetal at 16–31 cm/sec with less than 15 cm/sec of variation. <b>(b)</b> Image in a patient with tricuspid regurgitation shows abnormal periodic variation, with intermittent reversal of flow direction due to central venous pressure being transmitted through hepatic sinusoids.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig4b.jpeg" height="1390" width="1857" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Spectral Doppler US waveform images of portal venous flow in two patients. <i>AC</i> = angle of correction, <i>MPV</i> = main portal vein, <i>PV</i> = portal velocity. <b>(a)</b> Image shows that typical antegrade portal venous flow is hepatopetal at 16–31 cm/sec with less than 15 cm/sec of variation. <b>(b)</b> Image in a patient with tricuspid regurgitation shows abnormal periodic variation, with intermittent reversal of flow direction due to central venous pressure being transmitted through hepatic sinusoids.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig5.jpeg" height="759" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Axial CT image in a patient with chronic severe <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> shows hepatic vein–to–hepatic vein shunts (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig6a.jpeg" height="512" width="828" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma at different time points in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and portal venous <b>(b)</b> phases show early reflux of contrast material into the hepatic veins, with reticular regions of poor parenchymal enhancement in the periphery of the liver (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) that are much more conspicuous in the portal venous phase. <b>(c–e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR images in a different patient obtained in the portal venous phase <b>(c)</b>, with a 3-minute delay <b>(d)</b>, and with a 10-minute delay <b>(e)</b>. Peripheral heterogeneous enhancement is most evident during the portal venous phase (arrows in <b>c</b>); as time progresses, the distribution of contrast material in the liver becomes more homogeneous. <b>(f)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image in the same patient as in <b>c–e</b> shows edematous congested regions of the liver (arrows) with high T2 signal intensity, findings that correspond well to the regions of heterogeneous perfusion on the contrast-enhanced images <b>(c–e)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig6b.jpeg" height="512" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma at different time points in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and portal venous <b>(b)</b> phases show early reflux of contrast material into the hepatic veins, with reticular regions of poor parenchymal enhancement in the periphery of the liver (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) that are much more conspicuous in the portal venous phase. <b>(c–e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR images in a different patient obtained in the portal venous phase <b>(c)</b>, with a 3-minute delay <b>(d)</b>, and with a 10-minute delay <b>(e)</b>. Peripheral heterogeneous enhancement is most evident during the portal venous phase (arrows in <b>c</b>); as time progresses, the distribution of contrast material in the liver becomes more homogeneous. <b>(f)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image in the same patient as in <b>c–e</b> shows edematous congested regions of the liver (arrows) with high T2 signal intensity, findings that correspond well to the regions of heterogeneous perfusion on the contrast-enhanced images <b>(c–e)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig6c.jpeg" height="533" width="830" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma at different time points in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and portal venous <b>(b)</b> phases show early reflux of contrast material into the hepatic veins, with reticular regions of poor parenchymal enhancement in the periphery of the liver (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) that are much more conspicuous in the portal venous phase. <b>(c–e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR images in a different patient obtained in the portal venous phase <b>(c)</b>, with a 3-minute delay <b>(d)</b>, and with a 10-minute delay <b>(e)</b>. Peripheral heterogeneous enhancement is most evident during the portal venous phase (arrows in <b>c</b>); as time progresses, the distribution of contrast material in the liver becomes more homogeneous. <b>(f)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image in the same patient as in <b>c–e</b> shows edematous congested regions of the liver (arrows) with high T2 signal intensity, findings that correspond well to the regions of heterogeneous perfusion on the contrast-enhanced images <b>(c–e)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig6d.jpeg" height="533" width="846" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. Heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma at different time points in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and portal venous <b>(b)</b> phases show early reflux of contrast material into the hepatic veins, with reticular regions of poor parenchymal enhancement in the periphery of the liver (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) that are much more conspicuous in the portal venous phase. <b>(c–e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR images in a different patient obtained in the portal venous phase <b>(c)</b>, with a 3-minute delay <b>(d)</b>, and with a 10-minute delay <b>(e)</b>. Peripheral heterogeneous enhancement is most evident during the portal venous phase (arrows in <b>c</b>); as time progresses, the distribution of contrast material in the liver becomes more homogeneous. <b>(f)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image in the same patient as in <b>c–e</b> shows edematous congested regions of the liver (arrows) with high T2 signal intensity, findings that correspond well to the regions of heterogeneous perfusion on the contrast-enhanced images <b>(c–e)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig6e.jpeg" height="518" width="818" aria-labelledby="fig6e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6e</span>. Heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma at different time points in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and portal venous <b>(b)</b> phases show early reflux of contrast material into the hepatic veins, with reticular regions of poor parenchymal enhancement in the periphery of the liver (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) that are much more conspicuous in the portal venous phase. <b>(c–e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR images in a different patient obtained in the portal venous phase <b>(c)</b>, with a 3-minute delay <b>(d)</b>, and with a 10-minute delay <b>(e)</b>. Peripheral heterogeneous enhancement is most evident during the portal venous phase (arrows in <b>c</b>); as time progresses, the distribution of contrast material in the liver becomes more homogeneous. <b>(f)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image in the same patient as in <b>c–e</b> shows edematous congested regions of the liver (arrows) with high T2 signal intensity, findings that correspond well to the regions of heterogeneous perfusion on the contrast-enhanced images <b>(c–e)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig6e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig6f.jpeg" height="518" width="856" aria-labelledby="fig6f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6f</span>. Heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma at different time points in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images in the arterial <b>(a)</b> and portal venous <b>(b)</b> phases show early reflux of contrast material into the hepatic veins, with reticular regions of poor parenchymal enhancement in the periphery of the liver (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) that are much more conspicuous in the portal venous phase. <b>(c–e)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR images in a different patient obtained in the portal venous phase <b>(c)</b>, with a 3-minute delay <b>(d)</b>, and with a 10-minute delay <b>(e)</b>. Peripheral heterogeneous enhancement is most evident during the portal venous phase (arrows in <b>c</b>); as time progresses, the distribution of contrast material in the liver becomes more homogeneous. <b>(f)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image in the same patient as in <b>c–e</b> shows edematous congested regions of the liver (arrows) with high T2 signal intensity, findings that correspond well to the regions of heterogeneous perfusion on the contrast-enhanced images <b>(c–e)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig6f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig7a.jpeg" height="702" width="567" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Pseudothrombosis in a patient with <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows decreased attenuation due to lymphedema surrounding the portal triads (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a corresponding area of hyperintensity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image obtained with a 10-minute delayed phase during the same examination shows enhancement in the same region (arrow). This finding gives the false appearance of a nonenhancing thrombus in the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig7b.jpeg" height="702" width="645" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Pseudothrombosis in a patient with <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows decreased attenuation due to lymphedema surrounding the portal triads (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a corresponding area of hyperintensity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image obtained with a 10-minute delayed phase during the same examination shows enhancement in the same region (arrow). This finding gives the false appearance of a nonenhancing thrombus in the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig7c.jpeg" height="702" width="638" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Pseudothrombosis in a patient with <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image shows decreased attenuation due to lymphedema surrounding the portal triads (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a corresponding area of hyperintensity. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image obtained with a 10-minute delayed phase during the same examination shows enhancement in the same region (arrow). This finding gives the false appearance of a nonenhancing thrombus in the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig8a.jpeg" height="585" width="863" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Resolution of hepatic perfusion abnormalities after pericardiectomy in a patient with constrictive pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal preoperative CT image shows a thickened pericardium (arrowhead), a peripheral hepatic perfusion abnormality (arrow), and subcutaneous edema. <b>(b)</b> Coronal postoperative CT image shows resolution of the findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig8b.jpeg" height="585" width="812" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Resolution of hepatic perfusion abnormalities after pericardiectomy in a patient with constrictive pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal preoperative CT image shows a thickened pericardium (arrowhead), a peripheral hepatic perfusion abnormality (arrow), and subcutaneous edema. <b>(b)</b> Coronal postoperative CT image shows resolution of the findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig9a.jpeg" height="546" width="967" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Axial hepatobiliary phase gadoxetate disodium–enhanced MR images (<b>a</b> obtained at a different level than <b>b</b>) show low-signal-intensity bands that are seen clearly because of a lack of contrast material retention. The bands may be due to dilated veins and/or fibrous septa and tend to spare regions around the portal triads (arrows) while coming into direct contact with the hepatic veins (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig9b.jpeg" height="546" width="908" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Axial hepatobiliary phase gadoxetate disodium–enhanced MR images (<b>a</b> obtained at a different level than <b>b</b>) show low-signal-intensity bands that are seen clearly because of a lack of contrast material retention. The bands may be due to dilated veins and/or fibrous septa and tend to spare regions around the portal triads (arrows) while coming into direct contact with the hepatic veins (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig10a.jpeg" height="629" width="614" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Benign hyperenhancing hepatic nodule in a patient with long-standing <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hyperenhancing nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial hepatobiliary phase T1-weighted MR image shows that the nodule (arrow) retains gadoxetate disodium contrast material. The nodule was stable throughout a 3-year follow-up period and showed typical benign imaging findings, including homogeneous signal intensity and isointensity to the hepatic parenchyma on T2-weighted and precontrast T1-weighted MR images (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig10b.jpeg" height="629" width="611" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Benign hyperenhancing hepatic nodule in a patient with long-standing <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hyperenhancing nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial hepatobiliary phase T1-weighted MR image shows that the nodule (arrow) retains gadoxetate disodium contrast material. The nodule was stable throughout a 3-year follow-up period and showed typical benign imaging findings, including homogeneous signal intensity and isointensity to the hepatic parenchyma on T2-weighted and precontrast T1-weighted MR images (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig11a.jpeg" height="1175" width="1941" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. MR elastography of the liver. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the typical setup for MR elastography <i>(MRE)</i>. The passive driver is secured with an elastic band to the patient’s body over the liver. The driver is connected to a hollow plastic tube that allows transmission of pneumatic pressure waves generated by the active driver. The active driver is located outside the imaging room. <b>(b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image provides an anatomic reference. <b>(c)</b> Normal MR elastogram shows that elastography can be used to assess the wave amplitude and homogeneity of transmission through the patient’s liver and can give a qualitative impression of liver stiffness. The MR elastographic sequence encodes phase information of propagating shear waves to create a wave image. <b>(d)</b> Wavelength information is transformed into a quantitative color-coded map of shear stiffness (measured in kilopascals) called an elastogram. The regions of highest stiffness are coded in red, and the regions of lowest stiffness are dark blue and purple. This is a normal example in which the liver is homogeneously low in stiffness, similar to that of the subcutaneous fat and body wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig11b.jpeg" height="1180" width="1609" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. MR elastography of the liver. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the typical setup for MR elastography <i>(MRE)</i>. The passive driver is secured with an elastic band to the patient’s body over the liver. The driver is connected to a hollow plastic tube that allows transmission of pneumatic pressure waves generated by the active driver. The active driver is located outside the imaging room. <b>(b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image provides an anatomic reference. <b>(c)</b> Normal MR elastogram shows that elastography can be used to assess the wave amplitude and homogeneity of transmission through the patient’s liver and can give a qualitative impression of liver stiffness. The MR elastographic sequence encodes phase information of propagating shear waves to create a wave image. <b>(d)</b> Wavelength information is transformed into a quantitative color-coded map of shear stiffness (measured in kilopascals) called an elastogram. The regions of highest stiffness are coded in red, and the regions of lowest stiffness are dark blue and purple. This is a normal example in which the liver is homogeneously low in stiffness, similar to that of the subcutaneous fat and body wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig11c.jpeg" height="856" width="1167" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. MR elastography of the liver. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the typical setup for MR elastography <i>(MRE)</i>. The passive driver is secured with an elastic band to the patient’s body over the liver. The driver is connected to a hollow plastic tube that allows transmission of pneumatic pressure waves generated by the active driver. The active driver is located outside the imaging room. <b>(b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image provides an anatomic reference. <b>(c)</b> Normal MR elastogram shows that elastography can be used to assess the wave amplitude and homogeneity of transmission through the patient’s liver and can give a qualitative impression of liver stiffness. The MR elastographic sequence encodes phase information of propagating shear waves to create a wave image. <b>(d)</b> Wavelength information is transformed into a quantitative color-coded map of shear stiffness (measured in kilopascals) called an elastogram. The regions of highest stiffness are coded in red, and the regions of lowest stiffness are dark blue and purple. This is a normal example in which the liver is homogeneously low in stiffness, similar to that of the subcutaneous fat and body wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig11d.jpeg" height="855" width="1468" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. MR elastography of the liver. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the typical setup for MR elastography <i>(MRE)</i>. The passive driver is secured with an elastic band to the patient’s body over the liver. The driver is connected to a hollow plastic tube that allows transmission of pneumatic pressure waves generated by the active driver. The active driver is located outside the imaging room. <b>(b)</b> Axial T1-weighted MR image provides an anatomic reference. <b>(c)</b> Normal MR elastogram shows that elastography can be used to assess the wave amplitude and homogeneity of transmission through the patient’s liver and can give a qualitative impression of liver stiffness. The MR elastographic sequence encodes phase information of propagating shear waves to create a wave image. <b>(d)</b> Wavelength information is transformed into a quantitative color-coded map of shear stiffness (measured in kilopascals) called an elastogram. The regions of highest stiffness are coded in red, and the regions of lowest stiffness are dark blue and purple. This is a normal example in which the liver is homogeneously low in stiffness, similar to that of the subcutaneous fat and body wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig12a.jpeg" height="1128" width="1759" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Imaging correlation of congestive enhancement pattern. <b>(a)</b> Axial MR image shows peripheral hepatic perfusion abnormalities (arrows). <b>(b)</b> MR elastogram shows corresponding regions of elevated stiffness (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig12b.jpeg" height="1128" width="1990" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Imaging correlation of congestive enhancement pattern. <b>(a)</b> Axial MR image shows peripheral hepatic perfusion abnormalities (arrows). <b>(b)</b> MR elastogram shows corresponding regions of elevated stiffness (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig13a.jpeg" height="1007" width="1534" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Findings at conventional MR imaging and MR elastography in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial conventional MR image <b>(a)</b> and MR elastogram <b>(b)</b> in a patient with tricuspid regurgitation and suspected <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> do not reveal any evidence of hepatic congestion. <b>(c, d)</b> Findings in a different patient with constrictive pericarditis detected at echocardiography who was referred for cardiac MR imaging and MR elastography. <b>(c)</b> Axial MR image shows no findings of <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram shows marked abnormality with increased stiffness predominantly in the liver periphery (arrow), a finding consistent with hepatic congestion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig13b.jpeg" height="1007" width="1815" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Findings at conventional MR imaging and MR elastography in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial conventional MR image <b>(a)</b> and MR elastogram <b>(b)</b> in a patient with tricuspid regurgitation and suspected <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> do not reveal any evidence of hepatic congestion. <b>(c, d)</b> Findings in a different patient with constrictive pericarditis detected at echocardiography who was referred for cardiac MR imaging and MR elastography. <b>(c)</b> Axial MR image shows no findings of <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram shows marked abnormality with increased stiffness predominantly in the liver periphery (arrow), a finding consistent with hepatic congestion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig13c.jpeg" height="1116" width="1123" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Findings at conventional MR imaging and MR elastography in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial conventional MR image <b>(a)</b> and MR elastogram <b>(b)</b> in a patient with tricuspid regurgitation and suspected <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> do not reveal any evidence of hepatic congestion. <b>(c, d)</b> Findings in a different patient with constrictive pericarditis detected at echocardiography who was referred for cardiac MR imaging and MR elastography. <b>(c)</b> Axial MR image shows no findings of <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram shows marked abnormality with increased stiffness predominantly in the liver periphery (arrow), a finding consistent with hepatic congestion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig13d.jpeg" height="1116" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. Findings at conventional MR imaging and MR elastography in two patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial conventional MR image <b>(a)</b> and MR elastogram <b>(b)</b> in a patient with tricuspid regurgitation and suspected <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> do not reveal any evidence of hepatic congestion. <b>(c, d)</b> Findings in a different patient with constrictive pericarditis detected at echocardiography who was referred for cardiac MR imaging and MR elastography. <b>(c)</b> Axial MR image shows no findings of <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr>. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram shows marked abnormality with increased stiffness predominantly in the liver periphery (arrow), a finding consistent with hepatic congestion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig14a.jpeg" height="628" width="868" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Imaging in a patient with asplenia and complex congenital heart disease who underwent a Fontan operation 27 years previously. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show heterogeneous poor enhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) and increased T2 signal intensity (arrows in <b>b</b>) consistent with congestive hepatopathy. <b>(c)</b> MR elastogram reveals elevated liver stiffness primarily in the periphery of the liver (arrows), with a mean stiffness of 5.6 kPa. Sildenafil therapy was started with the intention of decreasing the hepatic afterload. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram obtained 2 months later shows decreased liver stiffness (mean stiffness, 4.3 kPa).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig14b.jpeg" height="634" width="870" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Imaging in a patient with asplenia and complex congenital heart disease who underwent a Fontan operation 27 years previously. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show heterogeneous poor enhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) and increased T2 signal intensity (arrows in <b>b</b>) consistent with congestive hepatopathy. <b>(c)</b> MR elastogram reveals elevated liver stiffness primarily in the periphery of the liver (arrows), with a mean stiffness of 5.6 kPa. Sildenafil therapy was started with the intention of decreasing the hepatic afterload. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram obtained 2 months later shows decreased liver stiffness (mean stiffness, 4.3 kPa).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig14c.jpeg" height="628" width="907" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Imaging in a patient with asplenia and complex congenital heart disease who underwent a Fontan operation 27 years previously. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show heterogeneous poor enhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) and increased T2 signal intensity (arrows in <b>b</b>) consistent with congestive hepatopathy. <b>(c)</b> MR elastogram reveals elevated liver stiffness primarily in the periphery of the liver (arrows), with a mean stiffness of 5.6 kPa. Sildenafil therapy was started with the intention of decreasing the hepatic afterload. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram obtained 2 months later shows decreased liver stiffness (mean stiffness, 4.3 kPa).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig14d.jpeg" height="633" width="905" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. Imaging in a patient with asplenia and complex congenital heart disease who underwent a Fontan operation 27 years previously. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show heterogeneous poor enhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) and increased T2 signal intensity (arrows in <b>b</b>) consistent with congestive hepatopathy. <b>(c)</b> MR elastogram reveals elevated liver stiffness primarily in the periphery of the liver (arrows), with a mean stiffness of 5.6 kPa. Sildenafil therapy was started with the intention of decreasing the hepatic afterload. <b>(d)</b> MR elastogram obtained 2 months later shows decreased liver stiffness (mean stiffness, 4.3 kPa).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15a.jpeg" height="593" width="843" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15b.jpeg" height="593" width="732" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15c.jpeg" height="536" width="818" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15d.jpeg" height="536" width="757" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15e.jpeg" height="563" width="784" aria-labelledby="fig15e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15e</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15f.jpeg" height="563" width="791" aria-labelledby="fig15f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15f</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15g.jpeg" height="491" width="655" aria-labelledby="fig15g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15g</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15h" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150207/asset/images/large/rg.2016150207.fig15h.jpeg" height="491" width="670" aria-labelledby="fig15h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15h</span>. Underlying conditions that mimic <abbr title="congestive hepatopathy">CH</abbr> in four different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a patient with portal emboli due to inferior mesenteric venous thrombosis (arrowhead in <b>b</b>) show multiple peripheral wedge-shaped regions with poor portal phase perfusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT <b>(c)</b> and MR <b>(d)</b> images in a patient with Caroli disease show irregular parenchymal perfusion with normal enhancement adjacent to the portal triads (arrow). <b>(e, f)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT image <b>(e)</b> and delayed phase CT image at a more cephalad level <b>(f)</b> in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome show irregular peripheral perfusion, with sparing of the caudate lobe (arrow in <b>e</b>) and nonenhancing thrombi within the hepatic veins (arrows in <b>f</b>). <b>(g, h)</b> Axial arterial phase CT <b>(g)</b> and maximum intensity projection <b>(h)</b> images in a patient with hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia show shunting through multiple vascular malformations (arrowheads in <b>g</b>) that results in early antegrade enhancement of the hepatic veins (arrow in <b>g</b>) and an enlarged hepatic artery (arrow in <b>h</b>) that is easily appreciated on the maximum intensity projection image <b>(h)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150207&amp;id=fig15h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Coakley F